#Step 0

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv('avocado-updated-2020.csv')
#Step 1

#Dataset contains information pertaining to Hass Avocados from 2015 to 2020. 
#Variables include; Date, Average Price, Total Volume, 4046(Small/Medium), PLU 4225(Large), PLU 4770(Extra Large), 
#Total Bags, Small Bags, Large Bags, Extra Large Bags, Type, Year, and Geography
#Step 2

#Rename PLU codes to associated avocado size.
df.columns = ['date', 'average_price', 'total_volume', 'small_size', 'large_size', 'xlarge_size',
       'total_bags', 'small_bags', 'large_bags', 'xlarge_bags', 'type', 'year',
       'geography']

#Assign Metro Region?
#df.geography.unique()
#Step 3

organic2017 = df[(df['year'] == 2017) & (df['type'] == "organic")]
organic2017 = organic2017.groupby(df['geography'])['small_size'].sum()
organic2017.sort_values(ascending = False).head(5)

#Disregarding Total US, The West was the major geographical region that sold the most organic small Hass 
#avocados in 2017 with a total volume of 1,870,206.29

#Step 4

df[['Year', 'Month', 'Day']] = df['date'].str.split('-', expand = True).astype(int)
df.groupby(df['Month'])['total_volume'].mean().sort_values(ascending = False)
#Month 5 (May) has the highest average volume of avocado sales with a total volume of 1,123,632

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, theme, geom_boxplot, geom_bar, facet_wrap, geom_point, scale_x_date
#Step 5

regionSales = df.groupby(df['geography'])['total_volume'].mean()
regionSales.sort_values(ascending = False)
#Los Angeles, New York, Dallas/Ft. Worth, Houston, and Denver are the "metro area geographical regions" that sold
#the most avocados. 

metro_regions = ["Los Angeles", "New York", "Dallas/Ft. Worth", "Houston", "Denver"]
topRegions_df = df[df['geography'].isin(metro_regions)]

(ggplot(topRegions_df, aes(x = 'geography', y = 'total_volume'))
    + geom_boxplot()
)

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>
#Step 6

cali_cities = ["Los Angeles", "San Diego", "Sacramento", "San Francisco"]
california_df = df[df['geography'].isin(cali_cities)]
#Step 7

organic_df = california_df[california_df['type'] == 'organic']
conventional_df = california_df[california_df['type'] == 'conventional']

merged_df = organic_df.merge(conventional_df, on = ['date', 'geography'])
merged_df = merged_df[["date", "average_price_x", "average_price_y", "type_x", "type_y", "geography"]]

merged_df['organic_markup'] = merged_df['average_price_x'] / merged_df['average_price_y']
merged_df.groupby(['geography'])['organic_markup'].mean().sort_values(ascending = False)

#The table shows that San Diego had the largest difference in price of organic vs conventional avocados
#in California with a markup in price of 64%
geography
San Diego        1.641286
San Francisco    1.542492
Los Angeles      1.523324
Sacramento       1.469659
Name: organic_markup, dtype: float64
#Step 7 Continued

(ggplot(merged_df, aes(x = 'geography', y = 'organic_markup'))
    + geom_boxplot()
)

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>
#Step 8

var_list = ['small_size', 'large_size', 'xlarge_size']

organic = organic_df.groupby(organic_df['geography'], as_index = False)[var_list].mean()
conventional = conventional_df.groupby(conventional_df['geography'], as_index = False)[var_list].mean()

organic['type'] = "Organic"
conventional['type'] = "Conventional"

concat_df = pd.concat([organic, conventional])
concat_df['total_volume'] = concat_df['small_size'] + concat_df['large_size'] + concat_df['xlarge_size']

small_df = concat_df[['geography', "type",'small_size', 'total_volume']]
large_df = concat_df[['geography', "type",'large_size', 'total_volume']]
xlarge_df = concat_df[['geography', "type",'xlarge_size', 'total_volume']]

small_df['size'] = "Small"
large_df['size'] = "Large"
xlarge_df['size'] = "XLarge"

small_df['proportion'] = small_df['small_size'] / small_df['total_volume']
large_df['proportion'] = large_df['large_size'] / large_df['total_volume']
xlarge_df['proportion'] = xlarge_df['xlarge_size'] / xlarge_df['total_volume']

final_df = pd.concat([small_df, large_df, xlarge_df])
final_df = pd.DataFrame(final_df)
#Step 8 Continued

custom_stack_order = ["XLarge", "Large", "Small"]

(ggplot(final_df, aes(x = 'geography', y = "proportion", fill = 'size'))
 + geom_bar(stat = 'identity')
 + facet_wrap('type')
 + labs(title = 'Proportion of Total Avocado Sales by Size and Type in California Cities',
         x = 'City', y = 'Proportion', fill = 'Size')
)

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>
#Reading in Outside Data
housing = pd.read_csv('MedianPricesofExistingDetachedHomesHistoricalData.csv')

housing_df = housing.iloc[:, 0:6]
housing_df = housing_df.dropna()
housing_df = housing_df.drop('CA', axis=1)
housing_df = housing_df.drop(housing_df.index[-1])
housing_df = pd.melt(housing_df, id_vars=['date'], var_name = 'city', value_name = 'median_price')
housing_df.head()
date city median_price
0 Jan-15 Los Angeles $441,610
1 Feb-15 Los Angeles $419,260
2 Mar-15 Los Angeles $419,370
3 Apr-15 Los Angeles $427,010
4 May-15 Los Angeles $432,570 
#Transforming Existing Data
california_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(california_df['date'])
california_df['month-year'] = california_df['date'].dt.to_period('M')

grouped = california_df.groupby(['geography', 'month-year'], as_index = False)
avocado_df = pd.DataFrame(grouped['total_volume'].mean())

#Combining Datasets
combined_df = pd.concat([avocado_df, housing_df], axis=1)
combined_df.head()
geography month-year total_volume date city median_price
0 Los Angeles 2015-01 1.340373e+06 Jan-15 Los Angeles $441,610
1 Los Angeles 2015-02 1.592215e+06 Feb-15 Los Angeles $419,260
2 Los Angeles 2015-03 1.382745e+06 Mar-15 Los Angeles $419,370
3 Los Angeles 2015-04 1.354606e+06 Apr-15 Los Angeles $427,010
4 Los Angeles 2015-05 1.640058e+06 May-15 Los Angeles $432,570 
#Visualization using Combined Dataset
(ggplot(combined_df, aes(x = 'month-year', y = 'median_price', color = 'city', size = 'total_volume'))
    + geom_point()
    + labs(title = 'Housing Prices and Avocado Consumption (2015-2020)', x = 'Date', y = 'Total Volume')
)

#Not sure how to clean up X and Y axis, but data visualization paints a strong picture. 

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>

Overtime, median housing prices in major Californian cities have increased greatly. More so in cities like Los Angeles and San Diego, than Sacramento. There doesnât seem to be a definitive relationsip between cities with high median home prices, and levels of avocado prices. Median home prices in Sacramento are higher than in San Francisco, yet you can see visually that Sacramento consumes a lesser volume of avocados. We can also see that volume of avocados consumed in each major city did not change much over the 5 year span. In conclusion, there seem to be strong trends associated withe each city, however less so between median home prices and total volume of avocados consumed.
